* a purely functional programming language is one of which the core semantics does not allow side-effects
* any general purpose programming language should be purely functional by design
	* anything reasonably expected from a general purpose high level programming language [Java, C#, ...] - can be provided by a purely functional programming language; 
	* purity is not only trying to avoid side effects but avoiding all of them, surely; we can rely on the total absense of side-effects; this gives additional benefits 
		* enables secure libraries
			\ links-to internal cfccueyjcvaohdzb
		* evaluation order automation
			\ links-to internal gvlvjsxsrqfqfght
* the most notable purely functional programming language is haskell